How often do you guys experience audiation? If so is it on demand? I wasn't sure how to define it so I found this
“Audiation” is a term coined in the 1970s by Edwin Gordon to refer to the creation of auditory imagery. It is similar (but not quite the same) as Zoltan Kodály‘s references to “inner hearing.”
"To put it another way: Audiation is to sound what visualization is to images." got this explanation from here https://www.musical-u.com/learn/the-secret-music-practice-skill-audiation/ (edited)

What’s really cool is overtime you build a natural sense of harmony and such without having to rely on memorizing theory
Like you know what certain scales and progressions sound and feel like to play and you develop your own harmonic language
Researching and practicing certain systems like tonal, jazz harmonies, etc are great ways to build your harmonic palette but by no means feel obligated to follow every rule to the letter. The way you give things your own natural spin is where your own unique sound comes out

ᕲo̵乙o҉) (real hurricane hours) 03-Apr-20 11:01 AM
that sequence is C major, just the white keys, major, happy sound, the C at both ends is your "homebase" starting and end point
its where you feel the song resolve/begin/end/start
like where you are returning to, to achieve the feeling called "harmony"
SED!📣 03-Apr-20 11:02 AM
ᕲo̵乙o҉) (real hurricane hours) 03-Apr-20 11:02 AM
now consider the same notes, but starting and ending on different ones. Lets change our "homebase" to A, now we've got A B C D E F G A
play those SAME notes, just focusing on A as your home plate instead, and now its sad, minor sounding
literally the same notes to make the happy C major, just in a different order, changing the entire dynamic of each note within
All 7 of those notes you can do that with, and that is the "Seven Major Modes"

ᕲo̵乙o҉) (real hurricane hours) 17-Apr-20 03:50 PM

wαєrm 17-Apr-20 03:51 PM
each line is a sine wave playing at the same time
the distance in frequency between each sine wave is actually the same, but it's a logarithmic scale
the numbers at the bottom are Hz
each sine wave you add to a sound in this pattern will make it more and more resemble a saw wave
and in theory u can replicate any sound imaginable with the right combination of sine waves
at specific volumes, frequencies, etc.

ᕲo̵乙o҉) (real hurricane hours) 01-May-20 01:41 PM
@Occifer I thought more about your question with when to call a note Ab or G# etc. etc. As far as with what I know, this is what I came up with for an explanation. Consider the C# Major scale of C# Eb F F# Ab Bb C C#, this is what I would call the notes instinctually, and I don't know if its "correct". I could also say C# D# E# F# G# A# B# C# and technically be correct. But we don't say B# for the note C or E# for the note F. Although in the case of the scale you like to play most often (From what you've told me, I believe its F# lydian.) These are the same notes, played in a different order. The way I would name these notes is F# Ab Bb C Db Eb F F#. But in this case saying F# G# A# B# C# D# E# F# would make more sense than when we were calling it C# major, and starting from that note. My reasoning for this is the fact that the lydian mode is a Major scale with a sharp fourth. And since the 4th of F# is B, calling it B# in this case would be logical in my mind. The E# not so much. I still just refer to them as whatever makes sense in the moment, and it's never had an effect on any actual ability or playing. Nonetheless, that's how Id describe it. TL;DR the scale you play is F# lydian, a lydian mode contains a sharp fourth. The 4th of F# = B, so you COULD say B# but why idk. (edited)

ethan 01-Jul-20 03:20 PM
hey i have a cheap cecilio or two
honestly the quality of an instrument doesn't make much difference unless the person playing it is really good
or if you paid like tree fiddy for a violin
imo what you should be doing is perfecting techniques one at a time
like vibrato and shifting and scales etc
you want it to sound good, so tone quality is paramount
find some sheet music online and try to learn a few songs at a time
stuff within your skill range for the time being because if you go too ambitious you'll sacrifice good sound for just playing the notes fast enough
@ᕲo̵乙o҉) (real hurricane hours)
honestly i would much much prefer joining an orchestra for learning but idk the options in your area for adult beginners (edited)
